The STEYR AUG 
is a gas operated semi-automatic

The STEYR AUG is famous for its modular concept, which allows it to be quickly disassembled into six main component groups without tools. Here are the six component groups »


BARREL: The chrome-lined barrel can be quickly changed without the use of tools and has a foldable barrel grip. Gas pressure can be adjusted, allowing functionality under adverse conditions, such as cold weather.

RECEIVER: The receiver has an integrated Picatinny rail (Mil. Std. 1913) on which to mount various devices, such as a scope or flash- light. The barrel is locked into the front and back of the receiver.

TRIGGER MECHANISM: Located in the rear of the stock, it’s designed for semi-automatic fire only.

BOLT: The STEYR AUG has a fixed locking bolt, with seven locking lugs. An optional bolt is available to convert the STEYR AUG from right hand to left hand ejection.

STOCK: Black synthetic bull-pup stock, contains the receiver group, trigger mechanism group, magazine and external bolt release lever.

MAGAZINE: The detachable magazine is a staggered box type and is made of transparent synthetic material. Magazines are available in 30 round (standard) and 42 round (optional) capacities.

postcontent:
Federal American Eagle .223 Rem 55gr FMJ.  20 rounds per box.  For some reason they are marked 5.56 (.223 Rem) on the box, but they are .223 Rem cartridges (product code matches other American Eagle .223 Rem, and cartridges themselves are headstamped .223 Rem).  Product code is AE223.

The bullets are LEAD CORE, not steel core (a lot of rifle ranges will not allow you to use steel core ammunition). They pass the magnet test. Fully reloadable brass cases, not the unreloadable steel cases (save and sell the brass if you don't want to reload them and recoup $3-$5 per box).

These will work in any .223 Remington or 5.56 firearm.

I currently have 30 boxes available (600 rounds total). Price is $16/box FIRM. If I can't get what I'm asking I'll just hold onto them, I'm in no rush.  Price is pretty reasonable considering others are asking $1/round + for similar ammo.

These are listed on gunbroker as well, and based on the current availability of .223 ammo, I believe they will sell quickly. If you don't want to wait 3-6+ months to get ammo for your rifle, don't delay. I was just looking at .223 bullets for reloading the other day, and some of them are already backordered to NOVEMBER!

I will be happy to ship this ammo @ prevailing Fedex Ground cost (email me with quantity and zip code if you need a shipping quote). Payment to be made by USPS money order for all non-FTF sales. 6 box minimum on orders I have to ship.

title: For Sale:  RE: ARs/Bushmaster at Walmart for $984.
postcontent:
Regarding a question I received via email response: "Which Walmart?" The answer is ANY Walmart that has a sporting goods department and that sells firearms (not all do). You need to find that Walmart in your area. The AR rifle is only sporting good merchandise to Walmart and is held in no higher esteem than a golf club notwithstanding its different treatment under law.  
They sell them with respect to MSRP and profit margin consistent with the Walmart brand. That brand's mission is to give the everyday average working family the best price possible. They don't jack up prices based on trending hysteria. There is no fanfare when you ask to see one and no discussion of its rarity or that the price may go up if Obama starts confiscating them...just a sporting goods department selling sporting goods. The price point is set according to manufacturer MSRP and the buying power of the retailer.  
I did note that the guns trickle in and are sold almost immediately. You must be patient and diligent. It may take several trips or phone calls. Act like it is Christmas and you are looking for that Cabbage Patch doll for your daughter. Remember those days? After I posted the note, the Bushmaster I referenced was sold. More are coming in. 5 or 6 different brands including Colts and Sigs came into this particular Walmart this week...and sold in short order. They are continuously on back order and as they come in are first logged and then offered to the shopper for sale. There is no mystery to it...the salesperson has no special interest in it...just merchandise at MSRP or lower. Happy Walmart shopping to fellow gun enthusiasts.

- The VZ 58 has a milled receiver. 
- Even with the milled receiver, it is almost one pound lighter than a stamped AK-47.
- The VZ 58 receiver is completely enclosed, preventing debris from entering the receiver.
- The bolt of the VZ 58 stays open after the last round in the magazine has been fired.
- The safety is more ergonomic, making a faster first shot possible with the VZ 58.
- The ejection port is HUGE. There is no chance of an empty case getting stuck in the action of the VZ 58.
- The VZ 58 gas piston can be removed or exchanged without tools.
- The alloy magazine of the VZ 58 is half the weight of the steel AK-47 magazine. (.42 lbs vs. .84 lbs)
- The VZ 58 is striker-fired, unlike the hammer-fired AK-47. This reduces the number of parts and possible points of failure.

title: For Sale:  Steyr M40 .40 Cal. Handgun w/ High Capacity Mags

The Steyr M is a series of semi-automatic pistols developed by Steyr Mannlicher GmbH & Co KG of Austria for police services. The pistol has a multi-stage safety system consisting of two automatic internal safeties, two external trigger safeties and a manual lock safety.  The pistol’s design takes advantage of modern manufacturing techniques: the slide is precision-milled from steel;[2] the frame is an injection-molded synthetic polymer[2] and parts of the trigger and striker mechanisms are pressed from sheet metal.[4] For the purpose of regular maintenance, the pistol is stripped down into the following components: the barrel, slide, recoil spring, frame and magazine.

While the Steyr M is frequently compared to Glock-series pistols (both are polymer-framed striker-fired pistols, with Tenifer finishes), there are several differences in the details of the design. For example, the M-series had a fully supported chamber in all chamberings from the start (Some Glock models also had this feature from the start, other Glock models evolved to having more supported chambers when compared to their original internal layout), unique triangular/trapezoid sights, a loaded chamber indicator below the rear sights (on third and later generation Glock pistols this feature is present on the extractor on the right slide side) and a different grip angle (111°).

title: For Sale:  RE: AR/Bushmaster at Walmart $984. slight clarity revision
postcontent:
Regarding a question I received via email response: "Which Walmart?" The answer is ANY Walmart that has a sporting goods department and that sells firearms (not all do). You need to find that Walmart in your area. The AR rifle is only sporting good merchandise to Walmart and is held in no higher esteem than a golf club notwithstanding its different treatment under law.
They sell them with respect to MSRP and profit margin consistent with the Walmart brand. That brand's mission is to give the everyday average working family the best price possible. They don't jack up prices based on trending hysteria. There is no fanfare when you ask to see one and no discussion of its rarity or that the price may go up if Obama starts confiscating them...just a sporting goods department selling sporting goods. The price point is set according to manufacturer MSRP and the buying power of the retailer.
I did note that the guns trickle in and are sold almost immediately. You must be patient and diligent. It may take several trips or phone calls. Act like it is Christmas and you are looking for that Cabbage Patch doll for your daughter. Remember those days? After I posted the note, the Bushmaster I referenced was sold. More are coming in. 5 or 6 ARs (revision here, not 6 different brands), of various brands, including Colts and Sigs came into this particular Walmart this week...and sold in short order. They are continuously on back order and as they come in are first logged and then offered to the shopper for sale. There is no mystery to it...the salesperson has no special interest in it...just merchandise at MSRP or lower. Happy Walmart shopping to fellow gun enthusiasts.

title: For Sale:  chinese norinco sks, 2 mags, 1100rds ammo+mag catch mod
postcontent: matching numbers chinese sks in excellent condition. barely ever shot, like new internally, wood stock in very good condition with a few handling marks, barrel and gun metal blue are 100%. custom modification to magazine catch lever on bottom of trigger assembly. if you are familiar with these rifles, you know they origionally come with a fixed mag and you have to load ammo from the top. you can convert the sks  to detachable aftermarket "duckbill mags" but the conversion leaves the mag extremely loose (specs vary depending on magazine mfg.), and prone to malfunction or fall out during operation. this problem is due to the mag catch lever not being able to  engage as far as it needs to. well, i fixed that problem, and both mags lock up tight resulting in flawless operation. i googled and utubed this mod and there isnt another one like it that i can find (pat on the back) and it looks stock, unlike other mods i did find online. in pic 2, the worn spot behind the mag catch lever is where the mag catch was origionally seated, as you can see, the mag catch is moved foward 3/8" to 1/2" resulting in longer catch spring travel, and will now engage any mfg "duckbill" mag firmly.  comes with 2 detachable mags and 1100rds wolf ammo. $940 nine18nine022583 jeff.
